    "Markowitz portfolio construction can perform poorly when it is naïvely implemented, for example by using empirical estimates of mean and covariance on a trailing window of past returns.",
    "But the critical practical issues of taming sensitivity and gracefully handling estimation errors are readily addressed using techniques such as regularization and robust optimization, described in more detail in §1.3.",
    "It implicitly assumes risk symmetry.",
    "Markowitz portfolio construction uses variance of the portfolio return as its risk measure.",
    "With this risk measure a portfolio return well above the mean is just as bad as one that is well below the mean, whereas the former is clearly a good event, not a bad one."
